April
YOU HAVE IN US WILLING AND CAPABLE PARTNERS, TONY ELUMELU ASSURES PRESIDENT OF GHANA.
Our Chairman, Mr Tony Elumelu in continuation of his strategic vision of engineering a robust economic and business relationship across the continent has assured the President of Ghana, His Excellency Nana Akufo-Addo of the Banks support for the growth and development of the critical sectors of Ghana’s economy. He said investor confidence in Ghana is rising, following the pro-business and pro-private approach taken by the government of President Akufo-Addo. This, coupled with policy initiatives announced in the 2017 budget, is making Ghana the investment destination in the region.

“We are very happy about all of this, and we would like to associate ourselves with your government and support you to succeed, both in banking and in other sectors of the economy,” the Chairman said when he called on President Akufo-Addo, at the Flagstaff House, on Monday March 13, 2017 to congratulate him on his victory in the December 2016 elections. “Africa lacks economic independence, and people like you, Mr President, can provide the new hope for Africa and we will stand by you. You have in us willing and capable partners who are proud and happy to identify themselves with you,” Mr Elumelu added.

President Akufo-Addo on his part, expressed his deep appreciation on the visit by Tony Elemelu and the UBA management, describing it as historic and the first by any financial institution, stating that “we are all in admiration of the work you’ve been doing, not just concentrating on Nigeria, but, looking beyond the borders to the countries like Ghana and beyond”. With UBA being the first Nigerian bank to set up in Ghana, during the era of Ex-President John Agyekum Kuffour, largely as a result of the positive business atmosphere created in the country, President Akufo-Addo noted that he was keen on recreating a pro-business climate in Ghana to spur on development.

“It is only by growing our economy that we can solve the problems of our economy, principally youth unemployment. We want to grow our industry and our agriculture, and have a solid financial system that will support the growth of these two sectors,” he said.
President Akufo-Addo noted that “UBA is the kind of partner that we are looking for to assist us in the delivery of our vision and mandate”.  
Sounding optimistic about Ghana’s future, President Akufo-Addo told the UBA Chair that “we want to build a Ghana beyond aid. We are tired of being beneficiaries of handouts and charity. We want to be able to stand on our own feet and deal with our issues ourselves”.

The president also showed his appreciation to the Chairman’s advocacy through Africapitalism and entrepreneurship, he said “Thank you for encouraging us to believe in the potential of Africa through entrepreneurship”.
